According to Tolentino, this ideal image complicates a woman‚Äôs ability to dress, act, and choose freely‚Äîfor herself. Susan Faludi‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Naked Citadel‚Äù presents an ideal of a different kind. Those in power at the Citadel have deemed it their mission to produce ‚ÄúWhole Men‚Äù (72, 80) through their own forms of restrictive, normative gender ideals. According to Faludi, those in power at the Citadel demand conformity of the cadets through a rigid, militaristic, and often violent environment. Indeed, the Citadel seeks to ‚Äúoptimize‚Äù its cadets, first by breaking them down, and then by making them into ‚Äúbetter‚Äù men. In this environment, there are frequently severe consequences for those who do not conform. Both texts, in other words, show how social influence can shape how an individual conceives of and performs their identity in a variety of ways. Here's roughly how your paper should be structured, depending on whether you're arguing in favor of the paper or against it.  Arguing For: Suppose you're arguing for one of the three papers; say, for instance, Frank Jackson's "Epiphenomenal Qualia". Your job is then the following: first, briefly state and explain the argument of the paper your writing about (continuing with our example, this means briefly stating and explaining Frank Jackson's argument in his article); second, state and explain what you take to be the best objection to that argument (again, continuing with our example, this means stating and explaining what you imagine to be the best possible objection to Jackson's argument); and finally, respond to that objection, making sure you thoroughly explain why that objection fails (in our example, this means explaining why the objection to Jackson's argument you've just considered doesn't succeed in knocking down his argument).  Arguing Against: Suppose you're arguing against one of the three papers; say, for instance, Frank Jackson's "Epiphenomenal Qualia". Your job is then the following: first, briefly state and explain the argument of the paper your writing about (continuing with our example, this means briefly stating and explaining Frank Jackson's argument in his article); second, present and thoroughly explain what you take to be the best objection to that argument  (again, continuing with our example, this means stating and explaining what you imagine to be the best possible objection to Jackson's argument); third, briefly explain how the author (in our example, Jackson) might respond to this objection, and finally, explain why this response fails.  Whichever of the two options you choose, a few criteria should be met:  Your paper should be of the required length (5-7 pages double-spaced, 12-point standard font); Your paper should clearly exemplify the structure I've described above (in fact, keeping to this structure should help you to write your paper, especially if you do not often write papers!) Slavery in the beginning was solely dependent on race. The beginning of slavery was merely a way to classify people into being servants or being normal citizens. For example, according to Morgan‚Äôs American Slavery, the children of slaves were technically free members of society.  They were allowed to leave the plantation or even just be raised by slaves, but they were technically not slaves but people in society. However, when compared to modern day slavery, the children of slaves were technically born into slavery and served the same family. Specifically, there were laws that were created that ‚Äúdeclared that children should be slave or free according to the condition of the mother‚Äù(1). This law had multiple benefits. For example, it allowed slave masters to impregnate female slaves, leading to the creation of more slaves for the master without the slave master being there for child support. Another benefit this law had to slave masters is that it allowed masters to have an increasing and prolonged number of slaves throughout their life. This created a loop where slave masters would procreate to gain profit and gain more slaves. Even if the slave trade had stopped, ‚Äúthe class of free negroes was‚Ä¶ already in existence and could not be eliminated‚Äù(2). There were also many economic factors that contributed to the development of modern day slavery. One of these factors was the need for cheap labor for labor-intensive projects and produce. These products were known as cash crops like tobacco, indigo, and cotton. These crops were labor-intensive, and there was a constant demand for a cheap and controllable labor force. Going off this, there was intense profitability within slavery. Slavery proved to be an economically efficient system for the produce economy. Slaves could be purchased at a one-time purchase rate and they were forced to work without wages. The original form of slavery had children possess the ability to become free and allowed for slaves to buy freedom for themselves. However, later forms of slavery had children who were born into slavery forced to become slaves as well. Moreover, the government created laws to trap as many black people in the plantations which in turn would indirectly eliminate free black people and keep them contained within the slave community.

make this in an essay format to submit: In recent years, there have been growing calls to ban the use of facial recognition in the U.S., due to ongoing concerns about discrimination, privacy, and civil liberties. Some states (e.g., Maine Links to an external site.) and cities (e.g., San Francisco Links to an external site.) have banned the use of facial recognition by law enforcement and government agencies except in select circumstances, while other localities have considered but not implemented such bans.  In this case study, your assignment is to use concepts and materials from class and your own research to 1) describe the basic contours of the debate about whether law enforcement should be banned from using facial recognition algorithms, and 2) take an informed position on the debate. While facial recognition is increasingly used by private companies as well as government agencies (and Congressional legislation has been proposed to curb private use), this case study asks you to specifically focus on the use of facial recognition by law enforcement and other government agencies.  Step 1: Do some research about bans on facial recognition and the arguments for and against them. Focus your research on two areas:  Find at least two reputable media articles with more information about proposed and/or implemented facial recognition bans.  Find at least two scholarly sources that address the issues at stake. For example, relevant scholarly sources could be academic articles that explain how facial recognition technology works, describe some of the issues that have arisen (e.g., mismatches leading to erroneous arrests, disparate levels of accuracy for people of different races, ethnic groups, and genders, etc), and/or theorize the broader ethical issues raised by facial recognition, including discriminatory impacts, government surveillance, civil liberties, and privacy.  Step 2: Drawing on the sources you find AND material from class, write a short essay that reflects on facial recognition from a policy perspective.  Your memo should be 800-1000 words (not including references). Make sure to cite all your sources!  Your essay must contain the following components:  Begin with a brief (i.e., 1-2 paragraphs) description of facial recognition technology and the controversy around the use of facial recognition by law enforcement. Be sure to answer the following questions: [2 points (.5*4)] In broad strokes (you do not have to get extremely technical), describe how facial recognition algorithms work. [.5 points] In cities and states where law enforcement agencies are using facial recognition, how are they doing so? For what purposes? [.5 points] In cities and states that have banned the use of facial recognition algorithms by law enforcement, what are some of their stated reasons for doing so? [.5 points] In cities and states that have banned the use of facial recognition by law enforcement with some exceptions, what are the exceptions (i.e., the circumstances in which law enforcement is permitted to use facial recognition)? [.5 points] Once you have described the debate around facial recognition, the remainder of your essay should take a position for or against banning the use facial recognition systems by law enforcement. Your position must be an informed one: that is, you are not simply stating your opinion, but making a persuasive argument in favor of your position that is supported by evidence and concepts from class and from your own research. If you take a position that is somewhere in between for and against (e.g., ‚Äúlaw enforcement should be prohibited from using facial recognition algorithms except in XYZ circumstances,‚Äù or ‚Äúlaw enforcement should only be permitted to use facial recognition algorithms that meet XYZ fairness and accuracy criteria‚Äù), make sure you spell out what the special circumstances or particular criteria you are advocating for, and why. The more specific, the better!
